	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Allright, I have read so many lies now it's not funny. This was posted on Oct. 13, 2000 so things may change. Ok, these Gargs are from 18-20, may be higher but not lower. Garg Eyes tend to drop either a lot or almost none. <BR>
<BR>
For all you necros out there here is a nic guide to use. I could take one red garg with 1/3 mana with 184 int.<BR>
1) Have your pet guard a spot.<BR>
2) Search for a Garg. (There is a good lookout spot near Specs where you could almost see the whole island.<BR>
3) Cast Engulf Darkness and start to run back to pet.<BR>
4) Turn around when you have time and cast Heat Blood then turn and run.<BR>
5) Send pet to attack the Garg. Chances are that the Garg will continue to attack you. Pet won't be able to taunt him off.<BR>
6a) If pet can't taunt garg off, just run in circles. When you get a chance cast Engulf again to make sure he can't catch you. Keep running.<BR>
6b) If pet does taunt him off, cast Heart Flutter, mediatate, and keep watch on pet's health.<BR>
<BR>
As far as getting skeles to hurt the gargs, I was watching a skele and garg fight, of course skele died. When I cast on garg his HP refilled. Happened 3 times, so I think a patch may have fixed that.<BR>
Be sure to have Feign Death memed. Good Hunting<BR>
<BR>
Bloodurst Bonehumper<BR>
Necromancer of the Guild of Avalon (Solusek Ro)
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
